        "theory": "# MAD Handbook Overview\n\nModern Application Development (MAD) is a multi-disciplinary field that combines software architecture, web technologies, backend logic, and DevOps practices to build scalable, resilient, and user-centric applications. This handbook serves as a comprehensive guide to the core principles and technologies covered in the MAD course.\n\n[NOTE]\nThis handbook is designed as a data-driven SPA. You can search for any topic using **Ctrl+K** or by browsing the categories in the command palette.\n[/CALLOUT]\n\n## Course Philosophy\nThe course focuses on the **Web as a Platform**. By understanding the constraints and capabilities of the web, we can apply sound engineering principles like **Separation of Concerns** and the **MVC Pattern** to build applications that work across devices and environments.\n\n## Topic Roadmap\n1.  **Apps and Architectures**: Understanding the building blocks of software.\n2.  **Web Fundamentals**: The history and mechanics of the Internet (TCP/IP, HTTP).\n3.  **Information Representation**: How data is encoded (ASCII, Unicode, UTF-8).\n4.  **Frontend Core**: HTML5, CSS3, and the Document Object Model (DOM).\n5.  **Backend Logic**: MVC, Flask, Routing, and Templates.\n6.  **Data Persistence**: SQL, NoSQL, and Database Design.\n7.  **Security**: Authentication, Authorization, and Common Vulnerabilities.\n8.  **Operations**: Testing, Deployment, and CI/CD pipelines.\n\n[TIP]\nUse the code pane on the right to see real-world implementations for each theoretical concept discussed on the left.\n[/CALLOUT]\n\n## Key Takeaways\n- MAD is about building robust client-server systems.\n- The web is the most versatile platform for modern apps.\n- Separation of concerns is the \"Golden Rule\" of software architecture.\n",
