        "theory": "# Beyond HTML\n\nThe web is constantly evolving. What started as a simple document sharing system has become a powerful application platform.\n\n## Evolution of Markup\n-   **SGML**: The complex ancestor of HTML and XML.\n-   **XML**: A strict, structured data format.\n-   **XHTML**: An attempt to make HTML follow strict XML rules.\n-   **HTML5**: The modern living standard. It breaks from strict SGML/XML rules to prioritize real-world browser behavior.\n\n## Web Components\nWeb Components allow you to create reusable custom elements with their own functionality and styling, encapsulated from the rest of the page.\n1.  **Custom Elements**: Defining new HTML tags.\n2.  **Shadow DOM**: Keeping component styles private.\n3.  **HTML Templates**: Defining markup that isn't rendered until needed.\n\n## Modern Frameworks\nFrameworks help manage the complexity of large scale applications.\n-   **Backend**: Flask, Django, Ruby on Rails.\n-   **Frontend**: React, Vue, Svelte.\n\n### Why React?\nReact is a declarative, component-based library for building user interfaces.\n-   **Declarative**: You describe *what* you want the UI to look like, and React handles the *how*.\n-   **Components**: Break the UI into small, reusable pieces.\n-   **Virtual DOM**: Optimizes updates to the real DOM for better performance.\n\n[NOTE]\n**The Future**: Technologies like **Web3**, **Decentralized Apps (dApps)**, and **AI-integrated frontends** are the next frontier of web development.\n[/CALLOUT]\n\n[TIP]\nAlways keep learning. The tech stack you use today will likely be different in five years. Focus on understanding the core principles (Architectures, Protocols, Data) as these remain constant.\n[/CALLOUT]\n\n## Glossary\n- **Framework**: A set of tools and rules that simplify software development.\n- **Component**: A self-contained, reusable piece of a UI.\n- **Shadow DOM**: A web standard that provides encapsulation for JS and CSS in Web Components.\n",
